    "body": "The following program demonstrates the effect of defining the same route across blueprints and the app - fetch http://localhost:5678/hello for each run:\r\n```\r\n$ python server.py app app\r\n$ python server.py bp\r\n$ python server.py app\r\n$ python server.py app bp\r\n$ python server.py bp app\r\n$ python server.py bp app bp\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt surprised me that Flask does not report route collisions.\r\n```\r\nimport sys\r\nfrom flask import Flask, Blueprint\r\n\r\n\r\ndef main():\r\n    bp_num = 1\r\n    app = Flask(__name__)\r\n    for arg in sys.argv:\r\n        if arg == 'bp':\r\n            bp_name = 'bp%d' % bp_num\r\n            bp_num += 1\r\n            bp = Blueprint(bp_name, __name__)\r\n\r\n            @bp.route('/hello')\r\n            def hello_bp():\r\n                return 'Hello ' + bp_name\r\n            app.register_blueprint(bp)\r\n\r\n        if arg == 'app':\r\n            @app.route('/hello')\r\n            def hello():\r\n                return 'Hello'\r\n\r\n    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5678)\r\n\r\n\r\nif __name__ == '__main__':\r\n    main()\r\n```",
